body:
That is a very interesting problem. Could you provide the versions for setuptools / wheels, 
both before and after upgrading? 
Apt-get update pulls new packages, so when somebody will try to reproduce this later, this information might help.
Also, you could maybe upgrade only one of them, maybe that would reduce the search space?
(ie. upgrading setuptools breaks it, upgrading wheels breaks it, if both are upgraded, then it breaks).

I have absolutely no overview how onnxruntime works, but I would guess this relates to the method how onnxruntime looks up which accelerators are installed. Probably there was a change in setuptools (or wheels) and it breaks something. If this is the case, it would be nice to hunt it down, because sooner or later every project, distribution will move to newer packages, so the bug will affect more and more people.

Hi @dvolgyes, thanks for reaching out.
You're absolutely right. I'll check the installed packages as well.
It should be possible to do apt-pinning, but TBH, that's too much work as long as we don't know for sure that it's related to the issue.

Going to report back.

@trifle I am just an interested third party, but I follow the 1.12 release closely because a) I also had GPU troubles recently, b) I very much need a python 3.10 support. So I can only guess based on my generic python experience, but these seemed to be logical debug steps. :)
